                            <comment id="12732866" author="noble.paul" created="Sat, 18 Jul 2009 09:32:20 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;What do we achieve with this move? &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12732882" author="ehatcher" created="Sat, 18 Jul 2009 13:22:29 +0100"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;What do we achieve with this move? &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A more sensible location for SolrJS - it fits best with Ruby and Python, not with data import handler and clustering.  Question is, any reason NOT to move it?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12733017" author="epugh" created="Sun, 19 Jul 2009 16:37:00 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;SolrJS is a really neat way of interacting with Solr, but doesn&apos;t really get the love it needs.  Like the current &quot;it doesn&apos;t work with IE8&quot; bug!   I think that having it packaged properly, and getting the docs more up to snuff will make folks use it more and hopefully lead to more development.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12733052" author="ehatcher" created="Sun, 19 Jul 2009 20:39:09 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Committed.  All seems well, but I&apos;ll leave open until Eric and others give the thumbs up that all is well with Solr&apos;s build, etc.  With it moved, it no longer is in the contrib-crawl.  That&apos;s no problem for me at this point, but what about for a release build of Solr - what do we want included in the main Solr distro?    Is it as desired right now?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
